\b There are complex historical reasons for the decline of sentimental fiction after the 1790s
\b0 . Margaret Cohen, writing about the history of the novel in France, suggests that the \'91hostile takeover\'92 of the genre by such realists as Balzac and Stendhal can be attributed to the need to impose order on the \'91chaos\'92 of literary and social relations in the early decades of the nineteenth century, a thesis that might also be applied to the English novel.
\fs21\fsmilli10667 \cf2 \up10 36 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Elizabeth Dolan finds in the works of Charlotte Smith, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Mary Shelley a shift towards \'91seeing suffering unsentimentally\'92, a focus on poverty, slavery, and gender oppression not merely to evoke sympathy, but to effect social change and relieve distress.
\fs21\fsmilli10667 \cf2 \up10 37 
